# Build a realtime voice support app

A focused build guide for creating a realtime voice customer support experience with OpenAI voice agents, support tools, transcripts, and production-ready handoff patterns.

## Intro

In this guide, we’ll cover the building blocks for a realtime voice customer support app: choosing a voice-agent architecture, streaming customer audio to a low-latency model, connecting support tools, and capturing transcripts for review. We’ll end with a practical app shape that can answer routine questions, create or update support records, and escalate to a human when needed.

### Resources
- [Voice agents](https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/voice-agents) - Learn how to build voice agents with the OpenAI Agents SDK, choose the right architecture, and connect voice workflows to the rest of the agent stack.
- [Realtime intro](https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/realtime-conversations) - Introduction to building realtime voice applications.

## Choose the voice-agent architecture

Start with a speech-to-speech realtime architecture for natural support calls where the customer expects interruption handling, fast replies, and spoken turn-taking. Keep the first version narrow: define the support persona, the allowed topics, escalation triggers, and the structured data you need to collect before a handoff, such as issue type, account identifier placeholder, urgency, and summary.

### Guide extract

#### Choose the right architecture

[Read full section](https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/voice-agents#choose-the-right-architecture)

## Choose the right architecture

| Architecture                              | Best for                                                  | Why                                                                                   |
| ----------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Speech-to-speech with live audio sessions | Natural, low-latency conversations                        | The model handles live audio input and output directly                                |
| Chained voice pipeline                    | Predictable workflows or extending an existing text agent | Your app keeps explicit control over transcription, text reasoning, and speech output |

Agent Builder doesn't currently support voice workflows, so voice stays an SDK-first surface.

### Resources
- [Realtime agents starter app](https://github.com/openai/openai-realtime-agents) - Starter app demonstrating realtime agent capabilities.

## Add realtime voice to the app

Create a short-lived realtime session from your server, then let the browser connect with microphone input and stream model audio back to the user. The client should show call state, support-agent status, and a transcript panel so the user can see what was understood while still interacting by voice.

### Code example

```javascript
// Server endpoint: mint an ephemeral realtime session for the browser
app.post('/session', async (_req, res) => {
  const response = await fetch('https://api.openai.com/v1/realtime/sessions', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: {
      Authorization: `Bearer ${process.env.OPENAI_API_KEY}`,
      'Content-Type': 'application/json'
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      model: 'gpt-realtime',
      voice: 'alloy',
      instructions: `You are a helpful customer support voice agent.
Collect the issue, answer only from approved support knowledge,
and escalate when the user asks for a human or the issue is unclear.`
    })
  });

  res.json(await response.json());
});
```

